<Author>Padman_LS
<Content>Nice new hotel I took advantage of the cheap opening internet deals and spent 5 nights at the Hoxton hotel, using it as base camp for my daily visits into nearby Clerkenwell. I arrived with my wife on a Sunday afternoon and check-in was a breeze. We were given a couple of key cards for a double room on the fifth floor at the back of the hotel overlooking Willow Street. Coming out of the lift, we made our way to the room though a dark-carpeted corridor lit by flourescent lighting behind coloured perspex. Outside the bedroom door is a hook for hanging up your re-cycled paper bag(s) to be filled in the early hours of the following morning with your complimentary 'Pret' breakfast of orange juice, banana and yogurt pot. The Do Not Disturb sign that you hang on your door was interesting - I'M BUSY on one side and **** OFF on the other! There were 2 windows in the room; one was locked and the other opened to a 3 inch gap. However, above the door was the air-con which could only be switch on using your room card and this worked well.The room was as described on the Hoxton website, and yes, the shower was good, giving you an option of getting drenched from above or blasted from the side.The bed was very comfortable with nice sheets and duck down duvet. Open the wardrobe, you'll find extra pillows and towels, an electronic room safe and also a mini fridge (which kept the clothes that were hanging up nice and toasty due to the heat it was pumping out!).Inside the fridge was a bottle of mineral water and small carton of fresh milk to have with the tea and coffee provided. Teabags come in a choice of breakfast or pepermint and the ground coffee is provided teabag style (caff/decaff) and is a welcomed change to your ordinary instant. There's a chaise longue in the room as well as a desk and chair. Inside the desk drawer are your tea/coffee bags, stationery (pencil/pad), a pocket guide to Hoxton, a hair dryer and the remote control for the flat screen telly which didn't work properly - couldn't get Channel4, BBC1's default volume setting was so loud that it was guaranteed to wake the neighbours when you switched on the TV in the morning!For those with WiFi enabled laptops, wireless broadband is complimentary thoughout the hotel. Unfortunately, this didn't work during my first couple of days; I could connect to the hotel's router but not access the internet. The hotel staff did allow us to use the internet free of charge from the PCs in the business centre.Being a cheapskate, I can't comment on the Hoxton Grille restaurant downstairs, but there are plenty of food places nearby - Indian and pizza restaurants just around the corner, loads of take aways and sandwich shops. Overall, my stay was a pleasant one; spoilt slightly by the rubbish telly, partial lack of wireless broadband and the bin men who I heard emptying the bottle banks at 4.30am. 
